<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-709-671  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 709 671.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Dec 17 1990 n331 p6(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ATandamp;T, MCI settle suits: carriers endorse fair practices. (MCICommunications Corp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Killette, Kathleen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>ATandamp;T and MCI Communications Corp have settled out of court inorder to solve lawsuits levied against each other claiming unfairadvertising practices.andP;  The long distance telephone companiesagreed to ask the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) toinitiate mandatory industry practice regulation regarding thetransfer of customers from one carrier to another.andP;  The twocompanies had charged each other with false and deceptiveadvertising; then ATandamp;T sued MCI for what it called abusivetelemarketing practices.andP;  Under the settlement, that each companywill ask the FCC to require confirmation of a customer's choice ofcarrier by either a third-party confirmation of the customer'schoice, an authorization letter, a call by the customer to an 800number stating his choice, or by having the customer call histelephone company or long distance carrier asking for a change.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (Cases)MCI Communications Corp. (Cases).andO;Ticker:    MCIC; T.andO;Topic:     Long-Distance Telephone ServicesUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionGovernment RegulationTelephone CompaniesAdvertisingLaw SuitCustomer Relations.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>